  "modules": [
    {
      "title": "Atomic models",
      "html": "<ul><li><b>Dalton</b>: atom indivisible sphere.</li><li><b>Thomson</b> (plum-pudding): positive sphere with embedded electrons.</li><li><b>Rutherford</b> (nuclear): dense positive nucleus, electrons orbit.</li><li><b>Bohr</b>: electrons in fixed circular orbits with quantised energy; photon emitted when electron drops from higher to lower level, E_photon = hf = E_higher − E_lower.</li></ul><p>Atomic spectra are line spectra characteristic of each element.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Who proposed the nuclear model?",
          "a": "Ernest Rutherford."
        },
        {
          "q": "Bohr postulate: energy is…",
          "a": "quantised (discrete)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "X-rays",
      "html": "<p>X-rays are produced when high-energy electrons decelerate in a heavy target (tungsten). They are electromagnetic waves of very short wavelength (~10⁻¹⁰ m).</p><p>Uses: medical imaging, crystallography, industrial inspection, treatment (radiotherapy).</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Give one danger of X-rays.",
          "a": "Ionising damage to cells; can cause cancer."
        },
        {
          "q": "Give one use of X-rays.",
          "a": "Diagnostic radiography."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Radioactivity",
      "html": "<p>Spontaneous emission from unstable nuclei of α, β and γ radiation.</p><ul><li><b>Alpha (α)</b>: helium nucleus, +2e, weakly penetrating (paper stops it), strongly ionising.</li><li><b>Beta (β)</b>: fast electron, −e, more penetrating (stopped by aluminium), less ionising.</li><li><b>Gamma (γ)</b>: EM photon, no charge, highly penetrating (thick lead), least ionising.</li></ul><p><b>Decay law</b>: N = N₀ e^(−λt). Half-life T½ = ln 2 / λ ≈ 0.693/λ.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "After 3 half-lives, fraction remaining?",
          "a": "(1/2)³ = 1/8."
        },
        {
          "q": "An isotope has half-life 5 days. Fraction after 15 days?",
          "a": "1/8."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Fission and fusion",
      "html": "<p><b>Nuclear fission</b>: heavy nucleus (e.g. U-235) splits into lighter nuclei, releasing neutrons and energy. Powers reactors and atomic bombs.</p><p><b>Nuclear fusion</b>: light nuclei (e.g. hydrogen) combine to form heavier nuclei, releasing enormous energy. Powers the Sun and stars.</p><p>Mass–energy equivalence: E = mc².</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Which process powers the Sun?",
          "a": "Nuclear fusion."
        },
        {
          "q": "Which reaction is used in current nuclear power stations?",
          "a": "Fission of U-235."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Semiconductors and diodes",
      "html": "<p><b>Conductors</b> (metals): overlapping bands, low resistivity.<br><b>Insulators</b>: wide energy gap.<br><b>Semiconductors</b>: small energy gap (~1 eV) — silicon, germanium.</p><p><b>Intrinsic</b>: pure semiconductor. <b>Extrinsic</b>: doped.<br>n-type: doped with pentavalent (P, As); majority carriers are electrons.<br>p-type: doped with trivalent (B, Al); majority carriers are holes.</p><p><b>p–n junction diode</b>: conducts when forward-biased, blocks when reverse-biased — used to rectify AC.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Silicon doped with phosphorus is what type?",
          "a": "n-type."
        },
        {
          "q": "What is the main use of a diode?",
          "a": "Rectification (AC → DC)."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
